post_text:
Kingfisher Public School families:

We are excited to announce that the USDA has granted a waiver to all schools that will allow all students to eat free of charge through Dec. 31, 2020. This waiver went into effect on September 1, 2020 so all students who regularly pay for breakfast or lunch will not be charged between Sept. 1, 2020 – Dec. 18, 2020.

Upon expiration of the waiver, students will return to their original paid/reduced/free status. When we are made aware of changes to the waiver, we will pass the information on to you.

Meals will be served based on the school calendar. In the event that we have a district-wide Virtual Learning Day, meals may be picked up at Kingfisher Middle School between 10 am – 12

Kingfisher Heritage School
August 17 at 7:42 PM ·

Hello Parents,
We just received notice that a 2nd Heritage Elementary teacher has tested positive and a couple more who have been contact traced to them. We are in the process of notifying parents of specific classrooms at Heritage. The other sites are not experiencing this outbreak at this time. Heritage will transition to distance learning platform tomorrow morning for 14 days. All other sites will be on regular time. If you have a child at Heritage and children in other sites, please keep the siblings at home as well. We will be releasing more information as it becomes available.

post_text:
Kingfisher Public Schools Parent and Guardians,

Kingfisher Public School plans on starting back traditional school with the students on Aug. 12th. We understand the situation with Covid-19 is everchanging. Plans will be developed that address safety protocols and distance learning in the event that school is forced to close for a period of time.

To get things started, we need feedback from parents. This survey gives us a starting point so that we can begin to plan accordingly. Parent participation is vital in gathering the information we need in order to have a successful start to the school year. This survey will be open until Wednesday, July 8th, at 9:00 pm.

It is only necessary to complete the form one time per family. If you receive the survey more than one time, please disregard the others.

Thank you for your time.

Kingfisher Public Schools

post_text:
Tomorrow is graduation! Here are a few reminders...........

Parents/Family:
**Gates open at 9 am. Park in the East parking lot, come through the East gate, and enter the field at the southeast corner (by the restrooms).
**We are not giving out tickets; each graduate can bring 10 guests. Please abide by this rule and sit together in one group.
**Due to the wind this afternoon, the chairs on the football field are simply lying on the ground right now. We will do our best to have them all set up by 9:00. Also, condensation may occur through the night, so chairs may be wet--plan accordingly.
***AGAIN--we ask that everyone follow CDC, state and local social distancing guidelines.
**At the conclusion of the ceremony, we ask that everyone exit the field in a timely and safe manner.

This event will be one to remember, so please help us make it the best graduation yet!

The ceremony will be livestreamed at kingfishersports.tv and we will share that live feed to this page at 10:00.

#jacketpride
#classof2020

post_text:
Hey Class of 2020:
Did you know that high schools across Oklahoma and across the nation are joining together tonight at 8:20 to honor YOU, the Class of 2020, amidst the coronavirus pandemic?

Tonight, April 10, at 8:20, the lights at the Kingfisher High School football field will be turned on and will burn for 20 minutes to show appreciation for the senior class, families, coaches, and athletes as part of the nation’s “Be the Light￼” campaign!

The lights serve as a symbol for the Class of 2020 that we are thinking of them during this time!

Please join us by driving by the stadium during this 20 minutes and honking your horn! Don’t forget to practice social distancing and please remain in your cars!￼

Why are we doing this everywhere at 8:20? Military time of 20:20 for
20 minutes for the class of 2020.￼❤️

We love our KHS Class of 2020￼ and it’s always a great day to be a Jacket!￼

post_text: CTTC info
shared_text:
Chisholm Trail Technology Center
April 6 at 7:52 PM ·

GOING THE DISTANCE — Creativity and innovation have always been our hallmarks, so it's no surprise that CTTC instructors have seamlessly transitioned to off-campus learning for all students beginning today.

For Brandi Millsap, Cosmetology instructor, that meant transitioning from the hands-on teaching she was doing the week before spring break to a Hybrid online/distance learning program approved by the State Board of Cosmetology for required theory hours.

Ms. Millsap also supplements that program with instructor-led demonstration videos, classes via social media and videoconferencing, emails, phone calls and any other way she can maintain contact with her students.

The rest of our faculty has proven just as innovative and adaptive. Check out this pdf document (bit.ly/CTTCdistancelearning) and our website to see all the ways CTTC is making learning accessible and program completion attainable – even during these challenging times. #cttcgoesthedistance #cttcstillhere4me #wereallinthistogether

"What is distance learning?
Distance learning is any method of learning that happens outside the traditional school building. The approach to distance learning will be different from school to school and district to district because student and staff access to technology and training will be different."

For more information on this topic, check out the link below to access the OSDE's page for resources.

Please note: distance learning does not only mean Online Learning. We realize that some families don't have Internet access nor do they have access to a computer. Our high school teachers will be working on plans this coming week so we can begin the process of distance learning starting April 6th. Stay tuned for details!
#jacketpride
#jacketstrong

post_text:
From the OSSAA page:

The OSSAA is actively monitoring the public health concerns related to COVID-19. Our Staff has been in contact with the Oklahoma Department of Health and based on the updates we have received, at this time will we proceed with all tournaments being played as scheduled. We do advise players, coaches, officials, contest workers and spectators to practice good hygiene by washing hands thoroughly and frequently; coughing and sneezing into kleenex and then immediately disposing of it are also recommended. Our Staff will continue to work with the State Health Department in monitoring the situation. The health and safety of all Oklahomans is a priority.

With that being said, LET'S BRING HOME A JACKET VICTORY TODAY!!! Our game tonight is at 7:00 at Deer Creek HS and admission prices are $7.00!
#state
#ourtimehascomeagain
#othca

post_text:
In preparation for state testing in April, KHS will now be offering a free, online ACT prep course two mornings before school each week for juniors. This free course will be monitored by an online facilitator and will run from 7:30 to 8:00 each Tuesday and Thursday (starting Jan. 28th). If your junior has previously taken the ACT, he/she can choose the subject area that needs improvement and use this time to focus on that area. If your junior is interested in attending these sessions, please send them to the office to sign up. We are also including this on our daily announcements this week!
#gojackets

post_text:
Announcement for Kingfisher Public School Parents and Students:

VAPING REGULATION effective today 8-14-2019

Use of any form of vaping/e-cigarette is prohibited on school property. Possession of vaping products on school property carries the same penalty as using them. A violation of this regulation will result in disciplinary action for the student including, but not limited to, conference with student, parent notification, detention, ISD or suspension.

The school procedure for the use of or possession of vape/e-cigarettes/tobacco will be the following:

1st offense – Parent notified, Law Enforcement called, 1 day ISD
2nd offense – Parent notified, Law Enforcement called, 3 days ISD
3rd offense – Parent notified, Law Enforcement called, 5 days ISD

Law enforcement will write tickets; maximum fine is $250 per offense.

Thank you for your cooperation!

shared_text:
Oklahoma State Department of Education
August 8, 2019 at 7:10 PM ·

Watch the latest video in our “Shaped My Life” series, which honors the teachers who have impacted the lives of notable Oklahomans.

In this week’s edition of “Shaped My Life,” Delbert Terrell, Commander Master Chief and Director of the U.S. Navy Senior Enlisted Academy, shares how his U.S. Government teacher from Kingfisher High School made him into the man he is today.

Do you have a favorite teacher who shaped your life? Share your stories in the comments below or use #shapEDmylife on Twitter to show our Oklahoma educators some much-needed love and appreciation.

“We can never show enough appreciation for educators. We are hopeful that 'Shaped My Life' will be an important reminder that teachers are heroes with the power, every day, to make a real and lasting difference that influences generations.” – State Supt. Joy Hofmeister

State track meet update:
Our kids did a fabulous job this weekend!
*FR Ally Stephenson, STATE CHAMPION in the long jump
*SR Madeline Loosen 3rd in the Girls 800 M Run and the 1600 M Run
*SR Colton York Runner-Up in the Long Jump
*SR Maddie St. Cyr 3rd in the 3200 M Run
*The girls 4x800 relay team of Katon Lunsford, Zoey Evans, Ashtin Witt and Madeline Loosen placed 5th
*The girls 4x400 relay team of Katon Lunsford, Rayland Garner, Ally Stephenson, and Madeline Loosen placed 5th
*SR Reece Lafferty 6th in 300 M Hurdles
*HS Boys Team ACADEMIC STATE CHAMPIONS, CLASS 4A BOYS
It's a Great day to be a Jacket!

post_text: On Monday, April 29th, KHS will join KMS, Heritage, and Gilmour schools to help raise money for the Playground of Dreams at Kingfisher Park planned by The Kingfisher Wheatbelt Chapter of National Ambucs. The fundraiser will last for two weeks and conclude on May 9th. So students (and parents), get all that extra change lying around the house! There will be buckets on the office counter to collect the money. The class who brings in the most change will get an open campus lunch on Friday, May 17th!

shared_text:
Chisholm Trail Technology Center
March 26, 2019 at 2:40 PM ·

Four Chisholm Trail Technology Center students recently qualified for the Business Professionals of America Spring Leadership Conference competitive events held in Tulsa, March 11-13. The CTTC qualifiers included, front, Lomega High School students Jessica Mather, state qualifier in database applications and Kelly Russell, state qualifier in digital publishing. Also competing were Kingfisher High School students Hayden Wittrock, back, placing fifth in database applications and Logan Hightower, state qualifier in computer repair and troubleshooting. These students represented the Digital Technologies and Computer Repair Networking programs at CTTC.
